06369nam a22008175i 9783110795110DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107951107 a10.1515/97831107951102doi  a(DE-B1597)625931  a(OCoLC)1378176368  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0000002bisacsh00aTruth in Serial Form :bSerial Formats and the Form of the Series, 1850-1930 /ced. by Malika Maskarinec. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (IX, 295 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aParadigms : Literature and the Human Sciences ,x2195-2205 ;v1500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: Serial Formats and the Form of the Series, 1850-1930 -- tI Serial Temporalities -- tHeine's Serial Histories of the Revolution -- tWorld History in Six Installments: Epistemic Seriality and the Epistemology of Series -- t"Nachkommenschaften": Stifter's Series -- tLe temps retrouvé: Claude Monet's Series between Impression and Belatedness -- tSequencing Failure: Photodynamism and the Knotting of Time -- tII Serial Formats -- tTrying on the Drawing Room: Realness and Truth in and out of Photographs -- tThe Bachelor: Gottfried Keller's "Der Landvogt von Greifensee" and Serial Erotics -- tMax Klinger's Ein Handschuh as Cycle and Series -- tDIN A: The Basis of All Thought -- tSerial Untruth: The Feuilleton and the Ornamental Image -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis volume has its starting point in the veritable explosion of serialized formats in all of forms representation, from painting to printing, beginning in the mid nineteenth century and the well-known fascination with series in biology, mathematics, music, art, or literature. The new media culture of the late nineteenth century, very much shaped by these serialized formats, sees itself confronted with questions of truthfulness in new and profound ways, just as perhaps the accelerated rhythm, anonymity, and broadened accessibility of new media today have created new possibilities for the dissemination of misinformation and, conversely, give us cause to interrogate anew our notions of truthfulness. By examining both the formal operations of both aesthetic and scientific objects in a series form, and the historical context of their publication or presentation, the contributions in this volume examine the often strained, but yet immensely productive relationship between the way in which a series negotiates questions of truthfulness: both by reference to the rules established in its series form or by means of its serial format. This volume provides ten detailed cases of the series form from the history of science and journalism, and the history of painting, photography, and literature as well.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Schweizerischer Nationalfonds (SNF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aSerialization.  aepistemics.  aform.  arealism.1 aEhninger, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranzel, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrajewski, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaskarinec, Malika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaskarinec, Malika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcBride, Patrizia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aM